Dear John Simkin:<br><br>
I would be interesting to explore if any parallels exist between the early British soldiers in North America and the Vietnam veteran.<br>
Could it be true that British merchants, politicians and citizens where focused more on making money than supporting their troops far removed to a strange land?  Did the British military have the requisite leadership and support from Mother England that would have made the difference?<br>
Certainly, British fighting men adapted their techniques in the New World but clung to old style, conventional methods of engaging the enemy... while their opponents where unorthydox.  Did the early British soldier have difficulty knowing who were and were not the enemy?<br>
Did the general population of England grow tired of the long and expensive conduct of a war so far from home...engaging Native Americans.. the French and ultimately their own brothers?<br>
As a Vietnam veteran it would be interesting for me to talk with one of these long departed British soldiers and see how many common emotional pains we shared.  Perhaps some precious and old dialogue exists in diaries and letters home that these men wrote, explaining their feelings.<br><br>
Good luck with your project.  God Bless you and your students.<br><br>
Edward Ramon - Vietnam 1966-67-69
